5:
Hahahaha! You've truly outdone
yourself this time, Luciada!
8:
My goodness... I really must stop
spending all my time down in the
Kaleidoscope or else I'll miss out on
the chance to witness absurdities
such as this!
13: Nnnh... I'm so sorry for everything!
17:
Sorry?! My dear child, you have
NOTHING to apologize for. This is
where you should be puffing out
your chest and standing proud!
20:
Put a smile on that face, Luciada!
You may have single-handedly
changed the very course of magical
history!
24: I d-did... all that? Are you sure?
28:
Those who have awakened their
powers in Shibuya will eventually
find themselves rooted in Palpebra's
reality.
31:
One day, their abilities will begin to
function in accordance with the
laws of our world—they will no
longer ignore the principles of our
reality.
35:
But this marvelous, wild invention
may have even expedited the
process! It planted seeds of the very
same dream in the hearts of mages
and the awakened alike!
39:
It will take root in their hearts, alter
their perception of the world, and
shape the future! My dear, you've
created a MYTH!
43: I... don't know that I'd put it that way...
47:
Magic itself will doubtless undergo a
fundamental change! People will
begin to believe that the overlap of
worlds will summon forth new
heroes!
51:
Y-you're blowing it way out of
proportion. I just wanted to express
my interests—I never could have
imagined anything like that!
55:
Are you certain? I can already see
it... Statues erected all around the
Academy—nay, the whole city!
58:
Yes... Statues of the great woman
who summoned this golem, in all its
magnificence—with the slight
exception of that unfortunate face.
63:
H-hey! Don't talk about my baby like
that! She's perfect, okay?!
67:
Anyway. Leaving your name in the
history books isn't all that
challenging. What's more important
is that YOU don't forget this day.
70:
Remember the joy you felt as you
expanded the horizons of your
world. Never stop striving for that
same feeling.
73:
Never stop breaking down the walls
of your world, and keep building
new ones. As many as it takes.
82:
Headmistress! If you have a
moment, there's a guest waiting for
you.
85:
I assure you, it's not someone who
should be kept waiting long.
90:
Welcome, Liam Ilde. I've been
looking forward to meeting you!
94:
I have to say, I'm almost offended
you never told me you were working
together with Headmistress
Voluntas all along...
99:
I was planning to tell you after
Magia Fest, but things got in the
way... I'm sorry!
103:
It WOULD be quite the scandal if
word got out that the Academy was
working with the Dark Mage of the
Kaleidoscope to tinker with the
world, wouldn't it?
106:
All that sneaking around I had to do
led to me being absent in the most
critical moment. I left all those kids
to deal with the mess on their own...
110:
And I understand you were forced to
get involved. As Headmistress, allow
me to offer both my gratitude and
my apologies.
114:
Don't mention it. Let's move on to the
main topic.
118:
A man with little patience for
ceremony, I see. You and I might get
along yet.
123:
Then, let us cut to the chase. I want
you to lend us your talents by
joining us at the Academy.
127:
...The Association for Magical Arts in
the Farlands already has its eyes on
me. The reason being—
131:
Your expertise with forbidden
incantations, of course.
134:
There's nothing wrong with having a
specialty like that. What young
mage ISN'T fascinated by the taboo,
after all?
136:
Imagine a box conspicuously
marked "FORBIDDEN"—it practically
begs to be opened! Only a dullard
bereft of any ambition would be
able to resist its call.
141:
But when you and Gram used too
many forbidden techniques, you
ended up seeing the Dragon's Iris.
145:
Hush now, Stella. We don't need to
mention that.
150:
I would argue the Academy is
precisely like that box you just
described.
153:
On the surface, you reject the
abilities of the awakened ones, but
underneath it all, they fascinate you.
What's more, your "box" seems to be
changing. Why is that?
157:
You're right. But do you know why we
do that? It's all to protect the worlds
of OUR young mages.
166:
The Suizen lad calls them
fundamental principles. In
incantations, they're often referred
to as "stars."
168:
They're something ingrained in
every person—the way they see the
world. Mages, of course, are
expected to go beyond their own
limited worldview.
173:
...But it's no easy task—like stripping
away the very armor that protects
you. Not everyone can gain such
power.
177:
Exactly. I once believed
otherwise—that only the weakest,
third-rate mages would fail at
it—but fifty years have taught me
otherwise.
180:
Ordinary people can suddenly burst
free of their shells, while geniuses
crawl inside a hole of their own
making and never come out.
183:
It has nothing to do with talent. It's a
fundamental part of being human
that we all have missing pieces.
196:
Even so, that's our goal. We want to
expand the world of human
potential. Voluntas Academy exists
for that very purpose!
199:
If one finds the confines of a box to
be more comfortable, we'll offer
them one. If not, they're free to step
outside!
203:
I, Nihilyana Voluntas, will help my
students walk whatever path they
choose!
207:
But you can't do everything alone.
We need others—especially those
who can teach us more about this
mysterious Shibuya!
211:
Fine. I'll do it. I can't deny that your
reasoning is logical.
214:
If you're looking to expand your
worldview... I might have an idea.
220:
Really now? I'm simply dying to hear
it!
226:
Oooh, now THIS is what I'm talking
about! How fascinating!
229:
Okay, Headmistress... How's this for a
proposal: We should try rebuilding
the tower that the Lord of Shadow
built!
233:
A tower? Which is to say, a
mechanism used to pierce the
fabric between two planes of
existence?
238:
A spiral spear, eh? My magic could
be of use here...
242: We'll need some DNA as well.
246:
Is this... something I should be
putting a stop to?
254:
Now then, time to go destroy the
world without anyone noticing!
